      <div resp="part:vija" type="translation">
        <!--update translation-->
        <p n="1">Prosperity! Fortune! Twenty seventh year, ninetieth day of the king who took the head of the Pāṇḍya<gap reason="lost"/>Kantaḷūr</p>
        <p n="2">Arumoḻitēvaccaruppētimaṅkalam, who graciously took the Eastern country, the Ganges and Kaṭāram</p>
        <p n="3"> ? (vakaiyālaṉ) of the category veḷḷāṉvakai kīḻ Iṟaikkuṭalāka nilattukkut tavirntu</p>
        <p n="4">so that it is put in the account, he graciously uttered of his glorious mouth the (officer in charge of) tirumantiravōlai Caḷukki-k-kulakāla</p>
        <p n="5">...cēkaranallūr kiḻavar Araiyar ... yilūraṉ Maṇṇai-koṇṭa-cōḻa...</p>
        <p n="6">of the Kṣatra-cikāmaṇi-vaḷanāṭu Cōḻa-mūvē...</p>
      </div>
      <div type="commentary">
        <!--Use<lb n="2"/> to indicate correspondence?-->
        <p>
            	<lb n="2"/> Kaṭāram is a port in Southeast Asia. The phrase "who graciously took the Eastern country, the Ganges and Kaṭāram" is formulaic and found in many cōḻa inscriptions".
      		</p>
